		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cincinnati</placeName>&#44; <date>March 7th. 5612</date>.</p>
			<p>Dear Sir&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I did not receive a letter from my brother in answer<lb/> to the one I wrote him during your visit here until a<lb/> few days back and therefore did not write before but<lb/> now according to promise I do.</p>
			<p>My brother says he shall reply to you but having been<lb/> very much engaged in the affairs of Sussex Hall<lb/> he has not until now had time to write to you&#44;<lb/> or me&#44; he says having interested himself for<lb/> <persName>Dr. Benish&#39;s</persName> Bible&#44; &#40;the Pentateuch of which is published&#44;<lb/> and having obtained more subscribers than will cover<lb/> the cost of it&#44; he is now going on with the other part<lb/> of the Bible&#44;&#41; he is sorry he cannot dispose of your<lb/> Bibles&#44; but with regard to the Occident he will<lb/> with pleasure try and do all he can&#44; but he says&#44;<lb/> the English do not like subscribing to foreign<lb/> periodicals although written in their own language&#44;<lb/> I suppose he will write you more fully on the<lb/> different subjects you wrote him about as he does not<lb/> mention much about them to me therefore I can conclude<lb/> that subject.</p>
			<p>No doubt you would be interested in a little of the<lb/> English news&#44; The Great Synagogue Dukes<add>&#63;</add> place has voted<lb/> 6000 pounds sterling towards building a Synagogue at<lb/> the <placeName>west end</placeName>.  A Public Meeting of the Jews was<lb/> called by <persName>Dr. Adler</persName> at Sussex Hall for the</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>purpose of establishing a Jewish college for the education<lb/> of ministers&#44; Readers&#44; &#38; teachers.  <persName>Sir Moses Montefiore</persName><lb/> presided.  I am glad to <del>say</del> see the so long looked for<lb/> Institution is now about being brought into existence&#44;<lb/> as a beginning 2000 pounds sterling has been already<lb/> subscribed&#44; and of course by now has increased.  I also<lb/> understand a gentleman is going to endow it.<lb/>  The case of <persName>Alderman Salomons</persName> for his taking his seat &#38; voting<lb/> came before a jury but he was not satisfied with<lb/> having 12 men that did not understand the law deciding<lb/> for him&#44; &#38; he took a verdict against himself&#44; subject<lb/> to the opinion of the judges&#44; the cause has been argued<lb/> by them but the judges of the course of Exchequer have<lb/> not yet give their <sic>judgement</sic>.</p>
			<p>I asked <persName>Mr. Henry Mack</persName> to become a subscriber to your<lb/> <sic>occident</sic> but he refused on account of taking so many<lb/> papers in.  I think if you had <sic>staid</sic> here longer<lb/> and had seen the people themselves you might have<lb/> got more subscribers.</p>
			<p>As <persName>Mr. Jonas</persName> wrote you last week all the <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName><lb/> News I have none to write.</p>
			<p>My Aunt &#38; Uncle <persName>Mr. &#38; Mrs. Jonas</persName> send their regards<lb/> to you&#44; and accept the same from me hoping you<lb/> may succeed in your undertakings which I consider are<lb/> for the benefit of the Jewish nation.</p>
          <p rend="indent(9)">I remain yours truly&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">Samuel J Oppenheim</persName></p>
			<p>To <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
